
                              Boxes

Menu - Desk Me
          Boxes     Stay-Quit -- Program information and Quit.

       Boxes
          Enter/Edit box info -- Displays the active groups 0-9.
               Allows the user to change the currently active group
               and enter box info.  Click the left mouse button on
               what you want to enter or edit.  Click the right
               mouse button to return to the menu.

          Edit box style      -- Allows the user to change the box
               fill pattern, screen fill pattern, and box style
               ie. with or with out text.
       
          Enter/Edit text     -- Allows the user to enter or edit
               the text to be put in the boxes.  Click on the
               box the text is to go in.  Then keyboard or mouse
               in any characters.  Another way to exit from
               the first screen is to press "q".

          Edit text style     -- Allows the user to change the 
               style of text in the boxes.

          Draw/Edit boxes     -- Allows the user to change the
               existing box info graphicly.  A help screen will
               appear first with info on which keys to press to
               do what .  The help screen can be called again 
               by pressing help.  The arrow keys work well for
               moving a group a short way.  But for a big move 
               the mouse is much more efficient.  Click the right
               mouse button, cross hairs will appear.  Move
               the mouse around.  Click and hold the left mouse
               button to start the rubber box.  Release the button
               to end the rubber box.  A hand will appear.  Move it
               around.  Click and hold the left mouse button, move
               the image to the desired position and release the
               left button.

          Auto Optimize       -- Allows the user to optimize the
               execution of code or have the computer do the
               optimizing or have no optimizing at all.  Optimizing
               is only available with one active group.

              More detail - if you optimize and DON'T SAVE as  DATA 
               the number you enter relates to the number of button
               in the y (horizontal) direction.  And should evenly
               divide into the number of y buttons.  So if y = 5
               you have two choices 1, 5  If y = 6  1, 2, 3, 6
               But the idea of optimizing is to speed up execution.
               If you optimize one button or one vertical row
               you will not speed it up it will be slowed down.
               You may not notice it the slow down though.

              Save as DATA - There are two values to enter
               1. boxes per block and 2. blocks per sector.
               Data is great, it will save a lot of program
               space.  But generally it is slower then not saving
               as data.  So optimizing is needed if you don't
               want a time lag before a given button turns black.
               Both of the numbers multiplied together represents
               how many buttons the program will go through before
               checking the mouse position and selecting another
               sector of buttons to go through.  The first number
               relates to how many buttons will be written on a 
               line of data.  If this line is to long you will 
               not be able to merge the file into the interpreter.
               If I optimize I usually let the computer auto optimize.

          Save as DATA        -- With this menu feature the user 
               can toggle between saving the code as data or not.
               Save as DATA is only available with one active group.

          Radio Buttons       -- If selected the code will be 
               written so the group will be radio buttons.
               Only available with one active group.
 
          Create Code         -- Writes a file to disk called
               BOXES.LST this is the screen you created. 

       Files +
          Save Box info       -- Saves your box info to disk.
               This allows the user to easily change a screen.
               You can create a screen for a program and when
               you come up with a new idea you can easily 
               change the screen to implement your idea.
               Very nice when putting out an updated
               version of your program.

          Load Box info       -- Loads saved groups.
  
          Free Ram            -- Lets you know how much free ram
                                 you have.

          Free Disk           -- Lets you know how much free disk 
                                 space you have.
          
          Run GFA BASIC       -- Calls the interpreter.  This lets
               you call the interpreter and merge BOXES.LST with
               out leaving BOXES.PRG  You must have at least 250,000
               bytes free.


     Why ?  I've always found creating buttons very tedious but
            worth it.  One night a friend an I were sitting around.
            One of those fly by the seat of your pants hack sessions.
            We came came up with the very basics of this program.
            Yes I will continue to work on it.  No I don't know
            how many hours are involved.


